member.remarks:
The disclosure rule contains a list of JSON Pointers (RFC 6901) that specify which fields to extract from the data.
Example disclosure rule: { "participantId": "buyer-wallet", "fields": ["/productId", "/price", "/quantity"] }
If a pointer references a non-existent field, it is silently ignored.

Evaluates JSON Logic expressions as defined at https://jsonlogic.com
Supported operators: - Comparison: ==, !=, ===, !==, <, >, <=, >= - Logical: and, or, !, !! - Arithmetic: +, -, *, /, % - Array: map, filter, reduce, all, none, some, merge, in - String: cat (concatenation), substr, in (contains) - Data access: var (variable reference) - Miscellaneous: if, missing, missing_some, log
Variable references use {"var": "fieldName"} syntax to access data fields. Nested field access is supported: {"var": "address.city"}

Calculations are applied in order, so later calculations can reference
the results of earlier calculations.

Example calculation:
{
  "name": "totalPrice",
  "outputField": "total",
  "expression": { "*": [{"var": "quantity"}, {"var": "unitPrice"}] }
}

Calculations allow blueprints to compute values from submitted data
using JSON Logic expressions.

Example:
```json
{
  "outputField": "totalPrice",
  "expression": { "*": [{"var": "quantity"}, {"var": "unitPrice"}] }
}
```

This would calculate totalPrice = quantity * unitPrice

This expression has access to all fields in the action data
via the {"var": "fieldName"} syntax.

Calculations can reference:
- Original submitted fields
- Results from previous calculations (if applied in order)

Example expressions:
- Simple arithmetic: { "*": [{"var": "quantity"}, {"var": "price"}] }
- Conditional: { "if": [{">": [{"var": "age"}, 18]}, "adult", "minor"] }
- String concatenation: { "cat": [{"var": "firstName"}, " ", {"var": "lastName"}] }

This is a subset of the complete action data, containing only the fields specified in the participant's disclosure rules.
Fields are selected using JSON Pointers from the disclosure configuration.
Example: Complete data: { "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@example.com", "ssn": "123-45-6789" } Disclosure fields: ["/name", "/email"] Result: { "name": "Alice", "email": "alice@example.com" }
